04937nam a22007695i 9780801460067DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979627758  a97808014600677 a10.7591/97808014600672doi  a(DE-B1597)478694  a(OCoLC)663901477  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPT3723.5.L6bU73 2010b 7aLIT0041702bisacsh04a843  aGN 15222rvk0(DE-625)rvk/42432:1 aUrang, John Griffith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLegal Tender :bLove and Legitimacy in the East German Cultural Imagination /cJohn Griffith Urang. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (236 p.) :b6 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSignale: Modern German Letters, Cultures, and Thought00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Eros and Exchange -- t1. Wares of Love: Socialist Romance and the Commodity -- t2. Love, Labor, Loss: Modes of Romance in the East German Novel of Arrival -- t3. Corrective Affinities: Love, Class, and the Propagation of Socialism -- t4. W(h)ither Eros? Gender Trouble in the GDR, 1975–1989 -- t5. Eye Contact: Surveillance, Perversion, and the Last Days of the GDR -- tCoda: A Chameleon Wedding -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt first glance, romance seems an improbable angle from which to write a cultural history of the German Democratic Republic. By most accounts the GDR was among the most dour and disciplined of socialist states, so devoted to the rigors of Stalinist aesthetics that the notion of an East German romantic comedy was more likely to generate punch lines than lines at the box office.But in fact, as John Urang shows in Legal Tender, love was freighted as a privileged site for the negotiation and reorganization of a surprising array of issues in East German public culture between 1949 and 1989. Through close readings of a diverse selection of films and novels from the former GDR, Urang offers an eye-opening account of the ideological stakes of love stories in East German culture. Throughout its forty-year existence the East German state was plagued with an ongoing problem of legitimacy. The love story's unique and unpredictable mix of stabilizing and subversive effects gave it a peculiar status in the cultural sphere.Urang shows how love stories could mediate the problem of social stratification, providing a language with which to discuss the experience of class antagonism without undermining the Party's legitimacy. But for the Party there was danger in borrowing legitimacy from the romantic plot: the love story's destabilizing influences of desire and drive could just as easily disrupt as reconcile. A unique contribution to German studies, Legal Tender offers remarkable insights into the uses and capacities of romance in modern Western culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aGerman fictionzGermany (East)xHistory and criticism. 0aLove in literature. 0aLove in motion pictures. 0aLovexSocial aspectszGermany (East). 0aRomance fiction, GermanzGermany (East)xHistory and criticism. 0aRomance filmszGermany (East)xHistory. 4aEurope. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9780801460067zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801460067423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801460067/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  